{{infobox state highway system |shields= |caption=Highway markers for AR 1, AR
11, and AR 112 |map=AR highways.png |map_notes=A map of highways in the state of
Arkansas |formed=1924, renumbered in 1926 |state=AR nn, Ark. nn, Hwy. nn
|links=AR }} The following is a 'list of [[state highway]]s in [[Arkansas]]'.
The state does not use a numbering convention. Generally the two-digit odd
numbered highways run north-south with a few exceptions; and even-numbered two-
digit state highways run east-west with a few exceptions.

Arkansas has long had a stigma of poor roads. The state has received the
designation of "worst roads in America" from several publications. "The
Best, Worst, and Deadliest Roads in America: The Rankings." Reader's Digest. [http://www.rd.com/your-america-inspiring-people-and-stories/the-best-worst-
and-deadliest-roads-in-america-the-rankings/article176005.html Article.].
Retrieved October 4, 2010. Interstate 30 and Interstate 40 had
historically drawn the most ire from truckers nationwide until a large
construction plan was completed on I-40. Lewis, Edward. "Roads In America -
The Worst And The Best." American Chronicle.
[http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/view/10326 Article.]. Retrieved
October 4, 2010. The rationale for this is rooted deep in Arkansas
history, primarily sprouting from the state's insistence on using "road
districts" rather than a state highway commission, and a lack of comprehensive
state highway plan until the formation of the State Highway Commission in
1923. McLaren, Christie. "Arkansas Highway History and Architecture, 1910-
1965." [http://www.arkansaspreservation.com/pdf/publications/Highway.pdf
Article.] Page 13. Retrieved October 4, 2010.
